<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-726-224  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 726 224.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Oct 2 1989 v6 n39 p139(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Clock running on stalled U.S. chip consortium. (US Memories Inc.)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Topic:     U.S. Memories Inc.andO;Semiconductor industryConsortiaBusiness PlanningDRAMFinancing.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Richard MarchandM;Computer-industry consortium U.S.andP;  Memories Inc. seemed like a good idea onpaper.andP;  U.S.andP;  computer and semiconductor makers would team up, build theirown memory-chip plant and free themselves from reliance on Japanesemanufacturers.andM;But three months after the project was announced, the list of consortiummembers remains at seven.andP;  Officials at Apple Computer Inc. said last weekthat the company had decided not to join the consortium, while CompaqComputer Corp. and AST Research Inc. remain undecided.andM;Industry heavyweights IBM, Digital Equipment Corp., Intel Corp. andHewlett-Packard Co. are among the original members of the consortium.andM;U.S.andP;  Memories still lacks more than half of its equity funding target of$500 million.andP;  Negotiations for a needed technology transfer with IBM arestill under way.andP;  And the consortium is waiting for legal clearance to ensurethat no federal antitrust laws are violated.andP;  The consortium says all theseissues have to be resolved in three months.andM;&quot;By the end of the year, it's going to be a go or no-go,&quot; said Joanne Howard,a spokeswoman for U.S.andP;  Memories, which is based in New City, N.Y.andM;The key reason for the deadline is foreign competition.andM;U.S.andP;  Memories wants to begin building its memory-chip plant by the end ofthe year so it can ship 4M-bit dynamic RAM (DRAM) chips in 1991.andM;Japanese manufacturers, which control about 85 percent of the worldwidememory-chip market, are expected to begin quantity shipments of 4M-bit DRAMchips in 1990.andM;In the short term, U.S.andP;  Memories faces a different type of pressure from theJapanese: sharply falling prices on existing 1M-bit DRAM chips.andP;  It was lastyear's high prices that helped spark the creation of U.S.andP;  Memories.andP;  Butthose prices have fallen from as high as $30 per chip to about $10.50, andforecasters say prices may continue to tumble to around $8 next year.andM;While the short-term payoff appears risky, there could be long-term security,said Richard Shaffer, editor of the Technologic Computer Letter in New York.andO;&quot;The long-term problems of dependency are not going to go away,&quot; he said.andO;</TEXT></DOC>